dfVadWGU_cA7yRpN1sUCXD1tsQb1TFxlGWt35HZcLUBK6HGKD8tqjaLiTAMiKJnKiJYouzZzOXlssjFym81mosGr6PdqWqjwCaYeMH1iQBBFet60_Ry0wfcwI3bMOGD66Yw_TWXO1dKx--ruU5d15LxXeCDRh5J22e6aYu9JMaNh76xsMxhGnhuu14yvB4dj9oC-Bqdlud9j9tI0w1fQXaNQwEk0aD72r0IqJAp_-kz5SZt2lp\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether to use an actual IMAPStore, since having the first and second loaders the same could prevent failures if the class already exists. I wonder if I need a custom classloader for a subclass that filters a class. There's also the issue of public API tests and no reflection being allowed. Should I consider using JavaCompiler? Dynamic class loading might be problematic under native conditions. It’s a lot to weigh!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering class loading issues**\\n\\nI’m thinking about why line 608 isn't covered. It seems like the missing test didn't report that `Class.forName` was unsuccessful. We may need a fallback mechanism. The source mentions two class loaders—the application's and the system's. I’m wondering if in JDK 1.1, `Class.forName` actually uses the caller's loader instead of the system's? This makes me question how to test this without direct reflection. Perhaps we should adjust the tests to dynamically compile/load the subclass?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class visibility options**\\n\\nI’m considering defining `TestIMAPStore` as a normal class and then hiding the folder class just from its loader. However, I can't actually change the loader. Could I use a package-private behavior instead? It seems that won't work either. I wonder if I can leverage the class loader of an anonymous subclass, but that feels limited too. Another idea is to create a folder class in the main or library package, but I can't source stubs or shadow real packages. The test folder, however, is loaded by the app loader.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dynamic class loading**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how to handle an UnsupportedFeatureError that comes from dynamic class definition and ensuring I have the class bytes. Maybe I can add a helper in the test source? For dynamically defining a class after an image build, I need to provide the bytes, which can be tricky. It seems using JavaCompiler might help, but it could fail before I can load the class. I wonder if I should look into using a Proxy class instead? That might be an interesting path!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class instantiation**\\n\\nI'm considering creating a constructor with a Session parameter and using MethodHandles for instantiation. The plan is to have a public constructor in my class that calls the protected IMAPStore constructor with a URLName. I might also need a method to create a folder. Generating bytecode manually sounds complicated, so I'm wondering if using ASM could help, even though it might be overkill. Plus, I want to explore implementing a custom loader for defineClass without direct reflection. It feels like there’s a lot to manage here!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering dependencies for testing**\\n\\nI think I need to consider importing NativeImageSupport since it's available through the plugin. I want to add a test method that only covers the fallback, especially since there’s an existing test that’s missing this aspect. I wonder if ASM is available transitively through Gradle; it might be better not to add that dependency. Instead, I could consider using `javax.tools`, but I'm unsure if that will work in a native context.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class structure**\\n\\nI'm considering how inner class names use $ in class files but not in test files. Is that allowed? It seems like test class names shouldn't use $. I can create a duplicate of a nested class dynamically since its source is in the same file. However, there's a reference to `IMAPStoreTest.sessionWithFolderClass` if I use private. I might need to avoid this by using the constructor parameter for Session, which is public. The nested public static class is `ChildLoadedIMAPStore extends IMAPStore`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class naming**\\n\\nI’m considering that the term \\\"missing\\\" might be a bit redundant. Perhaps it would be better to focus on classes that are actively loaded? There's also an idea of renaming \\\"missing\\\" to something like \\\"class not loaded,\\\" which feels clearer. I think simplifying terminology can help make it more understandable. All in all, I want to ensure the labels reflect their purpose effectively and are user-friendly!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining class definition**\\n\\nI'm trying to define a class, which seems good so far. But if the native image has resources and `defineClass` is unsupported, I need to catch that. I should ensure that there are no skipped tests related to the image info. It might be worth inspecting the NativeImageSupport API for further insights. I want to make sure I've covered all bases here to avoid any issues!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_YScgbg5xnpOZjSNogJ03Lx3c|fc_04f0b956743ace52016a0dcce36b4c8191abf265fc43852780", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n \"isUnsupportedFeatureError\" -S tests/src | head -20", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 18315, "output": 5780, "cacheRead": 7680, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 31775, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779289223204, "responseId": "resp_04f0b956743ace52016a0dcc881f6c819181e00b07609e8db1"}}
