YrTQkK1iF5Qj7faVPHyK_E5_0zDbgvlM-NQNSnv6C5TlrJWhpqgC755XCMPbi7rzdnmDFGcegw3mqZ3p57RZi81l2IIdQsu9Mhkg0j7gralXIUAgGx9xfhQdx_MGkVupNM26TOjhpYwHicjF5oUJlpTfVPH4vUHnIpVJRipBtjSY4tvVvS8EIUBYy4hq5NOO8cdLX0vO5-soC9GlrumxCfu3Z1bn9_z_jRIpCAGkaQPyBG12-BFJ4e5VZSYD7JY-91bKK8Mx53-wMAhrh5e26RFct5ihWNFCzEXe2sh2cUjUnb_2t6OCcHSJ_GD8osrPskGvip0oza92XTs-cF1PMyTZBa7ZI5NVkpRNkwMFMLAPOqLATlyHA6X4PKHLQ3CIc3aYsw0XMEcj6gLtE7Hasto_glZwpPAAnysGg2hOIX7gT03iC0sqX7ONOhBxH2Afa4FPM-8kRgaxHgcTDMCL5V3tSTtZqQPh_S-Jr48yOVbCwfN0qONl55Jy8xHafWPETkTeQgZ1WIqOgLXOai_L9czk_pSekb5d8Jke8UmmlzLzsALOiKET9xCVVrqkzS89E9gFfOVshxL1E_7j8w2BEWPE3y1UuqovkpzW5ml6m2OWTgTnGhZsUkYWDJcy387Ythom8BugChtr28ddt3Ucht8XSNmeVv0u95VoErYkB_zUc--EnynXgJXKXX8eimvzHkDRLuZd0ewNgTpmKmIPYBO59_-XO9mCLIn9pzJtWdQNrqvNJQpCvedfxh2fqWE46OAiA5W1heoE2vC_W7TeVjWIhRWTvulIcABWT5M0u7cT0kzFaJXr2JClmk6PKVW3-mMj8iaay_lAh50XoDoNlfHVVkBLrt5zQ5So4N7TJkqZ9Q-OU2rjdLL_OimsCKqziDHlYMOlg-ttnb1nyBOXLZ155gl0V7xc4fTAqnCOG6FpwCpLq7-eyfv7ieEgWEkKA89riRLfKCtKHcGZv05wo1EKdwaewOF2Dm5LlGGv1uwllE7PaMjPwwDG74gAFFK2BP_iy4pZRTMGZNAcnLYIWAGXRwEEP2G5J6ujyqUYPJfOXr3VE0Wj6E3f_7VM3ngRm3BX7-9yzzWV8niE3XzDNXXnxp5QD9VA_dsZB-LZJZp-qMenpJMVykiWDcRfSvfF4Cc71Fp4=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Java Constructors**\\n\\nIn Java, I know that multiple top-level classes can exist, but only one can be public. For example, if I have `class ChildLoadedIMAPStore extends... implements IMAPStoreTest.FolderFactory`, it might be package-private, and I wonder if the constructor should be public. If the class isn't public, reflection could return public constructors, but since the class itself is non-public, would that even matter? There seems to be a complexity with service and constructor access due to package and runtime differences.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining class access**\\n\\nI'm considering how package-private classes are inaccessible through reflection if the class loader's runtime package differs. It’s tricky because, while the constructor can still be public, the class itself isn’t public, which might lead me to misunderstand the accessibility there. If I think about `getConstructor`, it looks like it might return public constructors, even for non-public classes. I should double-check the specifics about what `getConstructors` returns for public constructors. There's definitely some nuance here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_1XbYxVwvK01hiIXvOFpMNuID|fc_04f0b956743ace52016a0dcd2eef8c8191b0152e811d064632", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.eclipse.angus/imap/1.0.0/src/test/java/org_eclipse_angus/imap/IMAPStoreTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.io.InputStream;\n", "newText": ""}, {"oldText": "    private static final String CHILD_LOADED_STORE_CLASS = ChildLoadedIMAPStore.class.getName();\n", "newText": "    private static final String CHILD_LOADED_STORE_CLASS =\n        \"org_eclipse_angus.imap.GeneratedChildLoadedIMAPStore\";\n"}, {"oldText": "    public static class ChildLoadedIMAPStore extends IMAPStore implements FolderFactory {\n        public ChildLoadedIMAPStore(Session session) {\n            super(session, new URLName(\"imap://localhost\"), \"imap\", false);\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public IMAPFolder createFolder(String fullName, char separator, Boolean isNamespace) {\n            return newIMAPFolder(fullName, separator, isNamespace);\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static class FolderClassHidingClassLoader extends ClassLoader {\n", "newText": "    private static class FolderClassHidingClassLoader extends ClassLoader {\n"}, {"oldText": "        @Override\n        protected Class<?> findClass(String name) throws ClassNotFoundException {\n            String resourceName = name.replace('.', '/') + \".class\";\n            try (InputStream input = getParent().getResourceAsStream(resourceName)) {\n                byte[] classBytes = input == null\n                    ? minimalClassBytes(name)\n                    : input.readAllBytes();\n                return defineClass(name, classBytes, 0, classBytes.length);\n            } catch (IOException exception) {\n                throw new ClassNotFoundException(name, exception);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    private static byte[] minimalClassBytes(String className) throws IOException {\n        ByteArrayOutputStream byteArrayOutputStream = new ByteArrayOutputStream();\n        try (DataOutputStream output = new DataOutputStream(byteArrayOutputStream)) {\n            output.writeInt(0xCAFEBABE);\n            output.writeShort(0);\n            output.writeShort(61);\n            output.writeShort(10);\n            output.writeByte(7);\n            output.writeShort(2);\n            output.writeByte(1);\n            output.writeUTF(className.replace('.', '/'));\n            output.writeByte(7);\n            output.writeShort(4);\n            output.writeByte(1);\n            output.writeUTF(\"java/lang/Object\");\n            output.writeByte(1);\n            output.writeUTF(\"<init>\");\n            output.writeByte(1);\n            output.writeUTF(\"()V\");\n            output.writeByte(1);\n            output.writeUTF(\"Code\");\n            output.writeByte(10);\n            output.writeShort(3);\n            output.writeShort(9);\n            output.writeByte(12);\n            output.writeShort(5);\n            output.writeShort(6);\n            output.writeShort(0x0021);\n            output.writeShort(1);\n            output.writeShort(3);\n            output.writeShort(0);\n            output.writeShort(0);\n            output.writeShort(1);\n            output.writeShort(0x0001);\n            output.writeShort(5);\n            output.writeShort(6);\n            output.writeShort(1);\n            output.writeShort(7);\n            output.writeInt(17);\n            output.writeShort(1);\n            output.writeShort(1);\n            output.writeInt(5);\n            output.write(new byte[] {0x2A, (byte) 0xB7, 0, 8, (byte) 0xB1});\n 